In July, a huge crack in Antarctica's Larsen C ice shelf calved the third-largest iceberg in recorded history. The scale of the giant ice block, dubbed A-68, is truly awesome: roughly the area of Delaware, the mass of 5.6 Mount Everests, and voluminous enough to fill Lake Erie more than twice.
